description.value: Terracotta fitting (?) in form of tragic mask; traces of pink glaze; single piercing at back.  A tragic mask of a Youth with an oval onkos and falling locks; the brows are sloping, the nose prominent, and the open mouth is wide. The back is plain, with a small hole at the centre angled downwards. The resting surface slopes slightly, so that the mask leans to its right.  Hollow; probably from a one-piece mould, with added back. Buff-brown clay, presumably a marl or a mixture; the front is covered with a white dressing, with substantial traces of pink paint on the face, and red remaining on the onkos and hair; the upper eyelids and the pupils are painted black.

description.value: Glazed composition fitting (?) in the form of the head of an Egyptian woman, with incised details. Short wig marked in squares which radiate out in sections from point at top of head, marked by a circle with a dot in the middle - was something fixed or located there? Wig is cut in steeply at the lower back of head, flat surface with segments of wig indicated only by vertical dashes, as though not going to be seen. Below, the neck is shaped as a peg-shaped cone with a ridge above it, diminishing in size to the bottom where there is a hole pierced in the middle. Finely modelled features, ears without earrings, slanting eyes and eyebrows, small neatly shaped nose and mouth, with small perforations pierced at each end. Glaze surface all gone, core -dirty yellow, fine hard, (where broken - a cleaner yellow.)

description.value: Glazed composition fitting (?) in the form of the head of an Egyptian woman or goddess (?), maybe for amuletic figure; wearing short wig marked in squares which radiate out in sections from point at top of head, marked by a circle with a dot in the middle (maybe something fixed there, headdress?); wig cut in steeply at the lower back of head, flat surface with segments of wig indicated only by vertical dashes, as if not going to be seen. Glaze surface all gone; yellow core of fine hard texture; very eroded surface, neck chipped.

description.value: Terracotta cylindrical fitting.  A cylindrical stand, tapering from bottom to top. At the top are mouldings, below which is the head of a young satyr surmounting a vinescroll that rises from a handled bowl. Below the bowl is a head of another young satyr or of a maenad: the workmanship is poor. The object stands on a low moulded plinth with a row of dentils. The back is plain except for mouldings at the top and bottom, the latter including the dentils of the front.   Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange to red-brown Nile silt; traces of a white dressing, mainly on the front, but some in the mouldings at the back.
